        counts[f.shape] += 1
    vehicle_size[p] = counts

In [43]:
def plot_random(data, n_samples = 5):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
    n_rows = len(data)
    for i,p in enumerate(data):
        samples = np.random.choice(len(data[p]), size=n_samples, replace=False)
        for j,imgidx in enumerate(samples):
            plt.subplot(n_rows, n_samples, i*n_samples+j+1)
            plt.imshow(data[p][imgidx][:,:,::-1])
            plt.title('{0} {1}'.format(p, imgidx))
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

We see that vehicle data contains images of the rear of the vehicles. Some images contain the whole vehicle, while some contains only a crop.

Non-vehicle data consists of mostly other features on the road. Sometimes there is also a small part of some vehicle in the cropped frames.

The H channels in HSV and HLS are pretty close. Below, we see that they differ by at most 1. The important thing is that H values are on a circle so we need to compute the distance mod 360 (in opencv implementation, H is divided by 2 so it is 180).

In [136]:
data = vehicle_data
for p in data:
    score = 0
    for img in data[p]:
        v_luv = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2LUV)[:,:,2].astype(np.float)
        v_yuv = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2YUV)[:,:,2].astype(np.float)
        mx = np.max(np.abs(v_luv-v_yuv))
        score += (mx <= 10)
    print(p, len(data[p]), score)

In [160]:
def get_hog_features(img, n_orient=9, pix_per_cell=8, cell_per_block=2, \
                     transform_sqrt = False, \
                     vis=False, feature_vec=True):
    # in skimage 0.12.3 L2 block-normalization is applied automatically
    if vis:
        features, hog_image = hog(img, orientations=n_orient, \
                                  pixels_per_cell=(pix_per_cell, pix_per_cell), \
                                  cells_per_block=(cell_per_block, cell_per_block), \
                                  transform_sqrt=transform_sqrt, \
                                  visualise=vis, feature_vector=feature_vec)
        return features, hog_image
    else:      
        features = hog(img, orientations=n_orient, \
                       pixels_per_cell=(pix_per_cell, pix_per_cell), \
                       cells_per_block=(cell_per_block, cell_per_block), \
                       transform_sqrt=transform_sqrt, \
                       visualise=vis, feature_vector=feature_vec)
        return features

def channel_hist(img, nbins=32, bins_range=(0, 256)):
    # Compute the histogram of the color channels separately
    return np.histogram(img, bins=nbins, range=bins_range)
